This is a good example of what people mean by an agentic operating system rather than “just an AI chatbot.” The interesting part isn’t any one component—it’s how they’re chained together into feedback loops.

Here’s the architecture broken down:

                    INPUTS
 ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │ Email │ Teams │ Calendar │ Reminders    │
 │ Git   │ Claude CLI │ Phone │ Meetings   │
 │ Notes │ PagerDuty │ Local Files │ etc.  │
 └─────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    │
          Watchers / Event Listeners
                    │
                    ▼
          Memory + Vector Databases
       (SQLite + embeddings + mem0)
                    │
          Semantic retrieval layer
                    │
                    ▼
             Planner (Hiku)
       "What should happen next?"
                    │
          Creates specialized subagent
                    │
                    ▼
          Claude CLI (subscription mode)
                    │
         Uses Git / Shell / MCP tools
                    │
                    ▼
      Fixes issue / drafts response /
      updates files / creates tasks
                    │
                    ▼
        Human reviews or auto-executes

A few things are especially clever:

* Claude CLI transcript embeddings. Instead of stuffing months of conversations into context, it retrieves only semantically relevant snippets. That’s essentially building a personal episodic memory.
* Hosting MCPs yourself. Running them on a Mac mini or server gives you persistent endpoints and keeps much of your data under your own control instead of routing everything through third-party services.
* Speech-pattern cloning from Teams. Rather than prompting “write like me,” the system retrieves examples of your actual writing and uses those as style references. That’s a retrieval problem more than a fine-tuning problem.
* Headless specialization. Instead of one giant agent doing everything, a planner creates temporary workers with only the tools and instructions needed for a specific task. That tends to be more reliable and cheaper.
* Event-driven automation. Nothing waits for a prompt. Emails, transcripts, commits, and alerts become events that can trigger workflows automatically.

